Sunset Boulevard
\i0\b0  is a {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Musical_theatre"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 musical}} with book and lyrics by {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Don_Black_(lyricist)"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 Don Black}} and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Christopher_Hampton"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 Christopher Hampton}}, and music by {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Andrew_Lloyd_Webber"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 Andrew Lloyd Webber}}. Based on {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Billy_Wilder"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 Billy Wilder}}'s Academy Award-winning {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sunset_Boulevard_(film)"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 1950 film of the same title}}, the plot revolves around Norma Desmond, a faded star of the silent screen era, living in the past in her decaying mansion on the fabled {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Los_Angeles"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 Los Angeles}} street. When young {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Screenwriter"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 screenwriter}} Joe Gillis accidentally crosses her path, she sees in him an opportunity to make her return to the big screen. Romance and tragedy follow.\cb1 \
\cb3 Opening first in London in 1993, the musical has had several long runs internationally and also enjoyed extensive tours. However, it has been the subject of several legal battles and ultimately lost money due to its extraordinary running costs.}